# Networking Devices

Different networking devices perform different functions.

---

## Hub

A **hub** is a basic networking device that connects multiple devices.

When a hub receives data, it sends the data to **all connected devices**.

Example:

```text
PC1 sends data

        Hub
       / | \
      /  |  \
    PC2 PC3 PC4

All devices receive the data.
```

Hubs do not intelligently forward network traffic.

Because of this, hubs are inefficient and rarely used in modern networks.

---

## Switch

A **switch** connects devices within a local network.

Unlike a hub, a switch intelligently forwards Ethernet frames.

A switch uses **MAC addresses** to determine where data should be sent.

Example:

```text
PC1 ----\
         \
PC2 ----- Switch ----- PC4
         /
PC3 ----/
```

If PC1 sends data to PC3, the switch attempts to forward the frame only toward PC3.

Switches maintain a **MAC address table**.

Example:

```text
MAC Address          Port

AA:AA:AA:AA:AA:AA    Fa0/1
BB:BB:BB:BB:BB:BB    Fa0/2
CC:CC:CC:CC:CC:CC    Fa0/3
```

Switches mainly operate at **Layer 2 of the OSI model**.

---

## Router

A **router** connects different networks.

Routers use **IP addresses** to forward packets between networks.

Example:

```text
192.168.1.0/24
       |
       |
     Router
       |
       |
10.0.0.0/24
```

The router allows devices from the two networks to communicate if routing and security policies permit it.

Routers maintain a **routing table**.

A routing table contains information about available networks and paths.

Routers mainly operate at **Layer 3 of the OSI model**.

---

## Modem

A **modem** connects a home or organization to an Internet Service Provider (ISP).

The word modem originally comes from:

```text
Modulator
+
Demodulator
```

The modem converts signals so that data can travel over the ISP's communication infrastructure.

Example:

```text
Internet
   |
  ISP
   |
 Modem
   |
 Router
   |
Switch / Wi-Fi
   |
Devices
```

Many home devices combine modem and router functionality.

---

## Wireless Access Point

A **Wireless Access Point (AP)** allows wireless devices to connect to a network.

Example:

```text
Laptop ))))
Phone  )))) Access Point ---- Switch
Tablet ))))
```

Access points are commonly used to provide Wi-Fi connectivity.

---

## Firewall

A **firewall** monitors and controls network traffic based on security rules.

A firewall can allow or block traffic.

Example:

```text
Internet
   |
Firewall
   |
Internal Network
```

A firewall rule might say:

```text
Allow TCP Port 443
Block TCP Port 23
```

This could allow HTTPS traffic while blocking Telnet traffic.

Firewalls are important components of network security.

---

## Gateway

A **gateway** is a device or system that provides access to another network.

In most local networks, the router acts as the **default gateway**.

Example:

```text
PC IP:      192.168.1.10
Gateway:    192.168.1.1
```

If the computer wants to communicate with a device outside its local network, it sends the packet to the default gateway.

Example:

```text
PC
|
| Destination: 8.8.8.8
|
Default Gateway
|
Internet
```

