# Hub vs Switch

| Hub                           | Switch                               |
| ----------------------------- | ------------------------------------ |
| Sends data to all devices     | Forwards data based on MAC addresses |
| Does not maintain a MAC table | Maintains a MAC address table        |
| Less efficient                | More efficient                       |
| Mostly Layer 1                | Mainly Layer 2                       |
| Rarely used today             | Commonly used in LANs                |

Example:

```text
HUB

PC1 sends data
      |
      v
     HUB
   /  |  \
 PC2 PC3 PC4

Everyone receives it.
```

```text
SWITCH

PC1 sends data to PC3
      |
      v
    SWITCH
      |
      v
     PC3
```

---

# Switch vs Router

| Switch                      | Router                  |
| --------------------------- | ----------------------- |
| Connects devices            | Connects networks       |
| Uses MAC addresses          | Uses IP addresses       |
| Mainly Layer 2              | Layer 3                 |
| Maintains MAC address table | Maintains routing table |
| Used inside LANs            | Used between networks   |

Example:

```text
PC1 ----\
         Switch
PC2 ----/
           |
         Router
           |
        Internet
```

The switch connects local devices.

The router connects the local network to another network.

---

# Router vs Modem

| Router              | Modem                                 |
| ------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Connects networks   | Connects to ISP infrastructure        |
| Routes packets      | Handles the ISP connection technology |
| Uses routing tables | Converts or terminates access signals |
| Can provide NAT     | Provides WAN connectivity             |

Typical home network:

```text
Internet
   |
 Modem
   |
 Router
   |
 Switch / Wi-Fi
   |
 Devices
```

In many modern home networks, a single device performs the functions of:

```text
Modem
Router
Switch
Wireless Access Point
```

