# Basic Network Configuration

At a minimum, a device commonly requires the following network configuration to access resources outside its local network:

```text
IP Address
Subnet Mask
Default Gateway
DNS Server
```

Example:

```text
IP Address:      192.168.1.10
Subnet Mask:     255.255.255.0
Default Gateway: 192.168.1.1
DNS Server:      8.8.8.8
```

## IP Address

The IP address logically identifies the device on an IP network.

## Subnet Mask

The subnet mask helps the device determine which IP addresses belong to its local network.

## Default Gateway

The default gateway is used to communicate with devices outside the local network.

## DNS Server

The DNS server translates domain names into IP addresses.

For example:

```text
google.com
     |
     v
DNS Server
     |
     v
IP Address
```

Without DNS, users would often need to access services using IP addresses instead of domain names.

These settings can be configured manually or automatically using DHCP.

