# Cybersecurity Relevance

Networking is one of the most important foundations of cybersecurity.

Security analysts frequently investigate network communication to identify suspicious activity.

Important network information includes:

```text
Source IP Address
Destination IP Address
Source Port
Destination Port
Protocol
Packet Size
Connection Time
Connection Frequency
```

For example:

```text
192.168.1.15 ---> 185.x.x.x
```

If an internal computer repeatedly communicates with an unknown external server, a security analyst may investigate the connection.

This behavior could potentially indicate:

* Malware communication
* Command and Control (C2) traffic
* Data exfiltration
* Unauthorized software
* Misconfigured applications

Network segmentation is also important for security.

Consider a company network:

```text
User Network
     |
     |
Firewall
     |
     |
Server Network
```

If an attacker compromises a user computer, network segmentation can help limit access to critical servers.

Security analysts use tools such as:

```text
Wireshark
tcpdump
Nmap
Netcat
SIEM platforms
IDS/IPS
```

to analyze network activity.

Understanding basic networking concepts makes it easier to investigate:

* Suspicious connections
* Port scans
* Unauthorized access
* Malware traffic
* DNS activity
* Network attacks

